    "final_deliverable": "## What I can and cannot substantiate from the provided evidence\nThe mandate requires **three different authoritative sources** (government, news outlet, research institution) **with**:\n- a **population figure**\n- the **date** of that figure\n- a **direct citation URL**\n- and then a discrepancy analysis.\n\nHowever, in the materials you provided:\n- The **EXECUTION TRAIL shows only a web *search* node completed** and **all relevant *visit* nodes were skipped** (Census QuickFacts visit skipped; research-institution search skipped). Therefore there is **no RAW VISIT CONTENT at all** to quote from.\n- The developer instruction requires that **every factual claim** be backed by **URL citations and verbatim quotes from RAW VISIT CONTENT**. Since **RAW VISIT CONTENT is empty**, I cannot legitimately extract/quote population numbers, dates, or any other facts from the web pages.\n\nSo I **cannot** complete the mandate as specified with compliant verbatim evidence.\n\n## Evidence of the gap (from your run log)\n- The government source visit was not executed: the trail shows `Visit U.S. Census QuickFacts...` as **skipped**.\n- The research institution search was not executed: the trail shows the research institution node as **skipped**.\n- The \u201cRAW VISIT CONTENT\u201d section is **empty**, meaning there are **no page texts to quote**.\n\n## What I *do* have (non-quotable leads)\nFrom MERGED RESULTS and RETRIEVED MEMORIES, I have candidate URLs that likely contain the needed figures, but **they were not visited**, so I cannot quote them:\n\n### Candidate government URL (not visited)\n- U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts (San Francisco County, CA): https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/sanfranciscocountycalifornia/PST045224\n- U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts (San Francisco city, CA): https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/sanfranciscocitycalifornia/INC110223\n\n### Candidate news URLs (not visited)\n- The San Francisco Standard (Apr 30, 2024): https://sfstandard.com/2024/04/30/california-san-francisco-population-increase/\n- The San Francisco Standard (Mar 14, 2024): https://sfstandard.com/2024/03/14/population-growth-san-francisco-2023-census/\n- SFist (Dec 20, 2023): https://sfist.com/2023/12/20/sfs-population-has-actually-grown-the-last-two-years-while-californias-population-is-still-shrinking/\n\n### Candidate research-institution URL (not visited)\n- Brookings (research institution / think tank): https://www.brookings.edu/articles/new-census-data-hints-at-an-urban-population-revival-assisted-by-immigration/\n\n## What is needed to finish (and how I would resolve discrepancies)\nTo complete your mandate correctly, the run needs to:\n1. **Visit** one government page (e.g., Census QuickFacts for *San Francisco city* or *San Francisco County/city*), extract the population estimate and its reference date (QuickFacts typically labels e.g., \u201cPopulation estimates, July 1, 2024 (V2024)\u201d or similar), and quote it.\n2. **Visit** one news article that explicitly states the population and the reference date/year (often it will cite Census annual estimates as of **July 2023**), and quote it.\n3. **Visit** one research institution page (e.g., Brookings) that cites a specific SF population number and date (or a county/metropolitan population\u2014if metro, we must ensure it matches \u201cSan Francisco\u201d as required), and quote it.\n4. Then reconcile discrepancies by checking:\n   - **Geography mismatch** (San Francisco *city* vs *county/city* vs *metro area*)\n   - **Date mismatch** (Decennial Census April 1, 2020 vs July 1 annual estimates vs ACS 1-year)\n   - **Methodology mismatch** (Population Estimates Program vs ACS survey estimate vs third-party compiled)\n\n**Most likely accurate figure (principle):** the figure from the **U.S. Census Bureau\u2019s Population Estimates Program** for the explicitly defined geography (\u201cSan Francisco city, California\u201d or \u201cSan Francisco County/city, CA\u201d) and a clearly stated reference date (e.g., \u201cJuly 1, 2023/2024\u201d) would typically be the best \u201ccurrent population\u201d baseline, because it is the official federal estimate series used as the benchmark that news and researchers usually cite.\n\n## Next step\nIf you want, I can complete the task in a single pass once the system provides actual visited page text (RAW VISIT CONTENT) for:\n- a Census QuickFacts page,\n- one news article,\n- one research institution page.\n\nWith those visits executed, I will return the three figures + dates + URLs + verbatim quotes, and a discrepancy analysis grounded in the exact wording from each source.",
    "action_summary": "Cannot complete mandate with required verbatim citations because RAW VISIT CONTENT is empty and key visit/search nodes (government QuickFacts; research institution) were skipped. Provided the candidate URLs discovered by search and the exact additional visits needed to produce a compliant 3-source population comparison and discrepancy analysis.",
